              why.</b><br>
            <br>
            Issue 1 — FastReports vs QuestPDF conflict<br>
            <br>
            Saravanan is right. This is the most important of the three.<br>
            <br>
            Sasi, I have checked every section of the document. The
            QuestPDF decision is correctly stated in Section 12.4, which
            reads: 'Transaction PDF prints use QuestPDF (MIT-licensed C#
            library) — not Crystal Reports, not FastReports.' That
            section is right. But the following sections still say
            FastReports:<br>
            <br>
            Section 5.11 Step 5: 'The FastReports template must include
            a visibility expression on these fields.'<br>
            Section 7.2: 'FastReports migration proceeds from the
            generalised JAT template.' And in the SPINRISE replacement
            row: 'implement IReportService using FastReport.Net or
            SSRS.'<br>
            Section 13 IST-3 answer: 'FastReports template must include
            a visibility condition on these two fields.'<br>
            Section 13 IST-9 answer: 'FastReports migration: single
            template RPT_RMI_PO.'<br>
            Section 14 Scorecard, Report Architecture row: 'FastReports
            migration: single RPT_RMI_PO template.'<br>
            <br>
            That is five places saying FastReports and one place saying
            QuestPDF. A developer reading this document cannot know
            which to implement.<br>
            <br>
            Your reply to PM Saravanan — 'The report tool has not yet
            been finalized. It will be updated at a later stage once the
            decision is confirmed' —<b> is factually incorrect.</b> The
            QuestPDF decision was confirmed by me in the v5 review mail,
            confirmed again in the VB FSD Claude Guide v3 published on
            12 April, and your own Section 12.4 records it as a decided
            CEO technology decision. The decision is confirmed. Section
            12.4 is correct. The other five sections must match it.<br>
            <br>
            <b>The fix is straightforward: </b>in every place where
            FastReports appears in Sections 5.11, 7.2, 13, and 14,
            replace it with QuestPDF. The SPINRISE template name changes
            from RPT_RMI_PO.frp (FastReports format) to a QuestPDF C#
            class. The visibility condition logic in Section 5.11 Step 5
            remains the same — only the technology reference changes.<br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <b>Issue 2 — SuppLotNoReqArrival default inconsistency</b><br>
            <br>
            Saravanan is right on this one too.<br>
            <br>
            Sasi, your reply says 'Decided to set default value as Y.
            Clearly specified at document level.' But the document says
            N in Section 11 and Y in Section 4. A document cannot be its
            own contradiction. Section 11 is the single source of truth
            for SPINRISE defaults — it is the table that a new-customer
            onboarding engineer will reference when configuring
            SPINRISE. If Section 11 says N and the correct default is Y,
            we will have misconfigured installations.<br>
            <br>
            The fix: change Section 11 SuppLotNoReqArrival default from
            N to Y. Then add a note in the same row: 'Existing Kalsofte
            VB6 customers currently configured with N must be explicitly
            updated at SPINRISE onboarding.' This preserves both the
            correct SPINRISE default and the migration note for existing
            sites. Section 4 and Section 11 will then be consistent.<br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <b>Issue 3 — Cover page version label</b><br>
            <br>
            Saravanan is right on this too.<br>
            <br>
            Sasi, I understand your reasoning. The 'FSD v3 Template'
            label refers to the VB FSD Claude Guide template version.
            But a developer reading this document for the first time
            sees 'FSD v3 Template — 14 Sections' on the cover and
            'Approved Version: v6' in the Document Identity table, and
            will wonder whether v3 and v6 refer to the same version or
            different things. That confusion is real and must be
            removed.<br>
            <br>
            The guide version does not belong on the cover page of the
            FSD. The cover page is the face of the document — it should
            identify the document, not the methodology framework. The
            fix: change 'FSD v3 Template — 14 Sections' to 'FSD v6 — 14
            Sections'. The guide framework version can be noted in a
            document properties field or not at all.<br>
            <br>
            <br>
            <b>Summary of what Sasi must correct in v7</b><br>
            <br>
            All three are text replacements. None require new analysis.
            Estimated time: 20 minutes.<br>
            <br>
            <b>Correction 1: </b>Replace all FastReports references
            with QuestPDF in Sections 5.11, 7.2, 13 (IST-3 and IST-9
            answers), and Section 14 Scorecard. Section 12.4 is already
            correct — leave it as-is and make the other five locations
            match it.<br>
            <br>
            <b>Correction 2: </b>Section 11 SuppLotNoReqArrival
            default: change N to Y. Add the migration note for existing
            customers.<br>
            <br>
            <b>Correction 3: </b>Cover page: change 'FSD v3 Template —
            14 Sections' to 'FSD v6 — 14 Sections'.<br>
            <br>
